# SCIP enrichment pipeline

## Flow

1. Detect languages present in the project.
2. Select and download/cache the matching SCIP indexer binary (and any runtime it needs — Node/JVM/.NET/etc. are self-provisioned).
3. Run the indexer, either as a detached background process after `infigraph index`, or in the foreground.
4. Import the resulting `.scip` file: enrich existing tree-sitter symbols in place (spans, docstrings), add symbols SCIP found but tree-sitter didn't, and add CALLS edges from SCIP reference data.

**Merge semantics — augment, never replace.** Existing edges/symbols are enriched or added alongside, not overwritten; disagreements with tree-sitter are captured in the learned-resolution cache (see that rule), not applied retroactively.

## Generic LSP bridge

For languages without a dedicated SCIP indexer, a generic tool spawns any LSP server and emits a SCIP index from `documentSymbol`/`references` requests. It only captures same-file references reliably — cross-file linking for these languages still depends on tree-sitter's own resolution.

## Adding a new indexer

Add an entry to the indexer catalog with the right download strategy; if it needs a new runtime type, the runtime-provisioning code needs extending too.

## Debugging a failed or silent enrichment

Check the background enrichment log first. A skipped indexer (missing project precondition) isn't a bug. If enrichment appears to never run at all, confirm the child process actually launched and exited cleanly rather than assuming the log's mere existence means success.
